  "text": "Three examples of myogenic behavior are illustrated in Figure 1 . 1) Figure 1A shows the prototypical myogenic response of a cannulated arteriole to a step increase in pressure. After the pressure step, an initial, passive distension is followed by two phases of constriction; upon release of the pressure step, the arteriole transiently collapses, then dilates. 2) In addition to this reaction, arte-rioles typically develop and maintain some degree of active force at their normal intravascular pressure. This is depicted in Figure 1B by the diameter response of an isolated arteriole that is maximally dilated after being cannulated and pressurized, but then spontaneously constricts to ϳ50% of its passive diameter when temperature is raised from 22 to 37°C. The constriction would typically be maintained for several hours. 3) A third way in which myogenic behavior is defined can be illustrated by a graph of diameter versus pressure for an arteriole with (active) or without Ca 2ϩ (passive) in the bathing media (Fig. 1C ). The range of pressures over which the active diameter curve has a less positive slope than the passive curve is termed the myogenic range. In arteries, this slope may be only slightly less positive than that of the passive curve [CITATION_1] , but in arterioles, it can be quite negative [CITATION_2] . Additional descriptions of myogenic behavior in isometric preparations are discussed in section IIIB.",
